Originally the forge at Birchwood was run by a family consisting of father, two brothers and a cousin, but is now in the hands of one of the brothers. The pattern of smithing has changed so that today the smith travels to many areas and derives much of his income from shoeing race horses. This smith, in fact, shoed the Grand National winner of 1976.
A set of shoes lasts for about six weeks and costs approximately Â£18. The forge is fired with small coke and the bellows are electrically operated. In addition to shoeing the smith makes wrought iron work.
